posts.author: dataonly
posts.title: The Latest Boasberg Order to be Vacated Was an Absolute SLAP Down by the 3-Judge Panel
posts.content:
<Obviously there was one democrat appointed dissenter.>

SCOTUS had reversed his original decision, citing he never even had jurisdiction (going from memory here). But, then he tried to hold the Admin in contempt over not complying with his order.

The SLAP down by the Appeals panel was an absolute embarrassment in judicial context. They essentially laid out the case that Boasberg was attempting to grab power the court did not ever possess. It is tantamount to a declaration of absolute corruption.

Chatgpt summary of the DC appeals panel order->

  1. Dangerous Judicial Overreach

The majority opinion—especially Judge Katsas—did not mince words:

“The district court used the threat of criminal contempt to coerce the Executive Branch to comply with an order it had no authority to enforce. And it directed that coercion toward the Executive’s exercise of its foreign affairs power.” That’s their encapsulation of the ruling: a court trying to weaponize contempt to wield control over foreign policy. beforeitsnews.com

  1. “Sword of Damocles” Over the Executive

The opinion continued:

“Dangling this sword of Damocles to compel the Executive to exercise its foreign affairs powers exceeds the court’s authority and is an abuse of discretion.” That imagery—the court holding a punitive threat over the presidency—really lays bare how they viewed Boasberg’s move. Justia Law

  1. Judicial Boundaries and Civil-Criminal Contempt Confusion

The court pressed that:

Courts have contempt power, yes—but it must respect the civil vs. criminal distinction, and not blur the line.

Once the Supreme Court vacated Boasberg’s original TRO, his contempt authority over the administration pretty much evaporated. Trying to enforce it still? That violates the limits of civil contempt and the need for procedural clarity.

Justia Law api.courthousenews.com

Edit: Have heard an en banc review by the full panel could be requested. Libs outnumber sane on the full panel. However, would go straight to SCOTUS if full panel reversed 3-judge panel which was effectively upholding the SCOTUS ruling. So, there really are no avenues to spare Boasberg of this complete and total rebuke.
